free_txt: ANNRI(BL04) beam line of MLF at J-PARC
Atsushi Kimura
Pulse-height weighting technique (PHWT) was applied.
Measurements with the carbon sample,
"Dummy replica sample", and "Blank (no sample)" were
used for back ground estimation.
The relative neutron spectrum was estimated using
the boron sample.
A relative capture cross-section was normalized to the
evaluated value in JENDL-4.0 at the first resonance.
Dead Time Correction was applied with a similar
method proposed by T. Katabuchi. (See. REL-REF)
Correction factors for self shielding and
multiple scattering were deduced using
the Monte-Carlo simulation code PHITS.
The NaI(Tl) spectrometer was used consisting
of two different sized NaI(Tl) detectors.
The larger detector: 330 mm (diam.) and 203 mm long,
placed at 90 deg. with respect to the neutron beam.
The smaller detector: 203mm (diam.) and 203 mm long,
placed at 125 deg. with respect to the neutron beam.
ANNRI(BL04) beam line of MLF at J-PARC
Spallation reaction in a mercury target
irradiated with 3-GeV protons (400 kW) . Produced
neutrons were slowed down in a supercritical para
hydrogen moderator (140 mm in diam., 120 mm in
height) . The proton beams were supplied at a
repetition rate of 25 Hz and under a proton beam
power of 400 kW with "single-bunch mode".
A beam size of 13 mm was defined by the collimator.
The neutron spectrum was reconstructed using the 478
keV gamma-rays from gamma rays from 10B(n,alpha1) 7Li
reaction.
Flight path length of 27.9 m.
Normalized to cross section at 0.49 eV resonance
Energy resolution of the pulsed neutron
Data acquisition system and dead time correction
227 mg of NpO2 powder (5MBq) mixed with 625 mg of
metal Al powder at the room temperature. Sample
powder was pressed into a pellet shape with a
diameter 20 mm, and sealed in an Al case (outer
diameter of 30 mm and 0.4 mm thick walls) .
A B4C sample containing enriched 10B up to 90%
with a diameter of 10 mm and a thickness of 0.5 mm
was used for neutron spectrum measurement.
A natural carbon sample  (93.0 mg/cm2, 10 mm in diam.)
was used as neutron scatterer to subtract background.

Data were obtained from AUTHOR.
Resonance energies, neutron and gamma widths
were determined with REFIT using Reich-Moor
approximation.
- The ANNRI beamline resolution function was taken
from the work of Kino. See REL-REF.
- The initial resonance parametrization data were
taken from JENDL-4.0.
- The initial delay and flight path were derived
using the results from the Au sample measurement.
- The resonance parameters of the negative resonances,
and the fission widths, spin and parity of all
resonances were fixed to the values in JENDL-4.0.
- All resonances have been considered to be s-wave.
- Doppler effect was modeled using the free gas model
with a temperature of 27 deg-C.
- In a first iteration, the averaged radiation width
was calculated as 40.3(5) meV from independent
large 17 resonances below 22 eV.
This averaged radiation width was used and kept
fixed for the other resonances below 110 eV.
The uncertainties are the ones provided by
REFIT as a result of the fitting.
